Because $s_t$ only affects $L_t, L_{t+1}, \ldots, L_n$,

$$
\begin{array}{l}
= \sum_{t=1}^{n} \frac{\partial s_t}{\partial W} \cdot \sum_{u=t}^{n} \frac{\partial L_u}{\partial s_t} \\
= \sum_{t=1}^{n} \frac{\partial s_t}{\partial W} \cdot \left( \frac{\partial L_t}{\partial s_t} + \underbrace{\sum_{u=t+1}^{n} \frac{\partial L_u}{\partial s_t}}_{\delta^{s_t}} \right) \tag{12.4}
\end{array}
$$

$\delta^{s_t}$ is the dependence of the loss on steps after $t$ on the state at time $t$.

